{{about|the 19th century American actress|the 20th-century dancer|Marjorie Bonner (Ziegfeld Follies)}}
'''Marjorie Bonner''' (died 1895), the stage name of Catherine F. Goodwin,{{citation needed|date=August 2017}} was a 19th century American stage actress.
In 1883 she was in the Rhea Company of actors. ''Monte Cristo'' was presented by the [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]] in December. Actor [[James O'Neill (actor)|James O'Neill]] performed the leading role with [[Frederic De Belleville]] playing ''Noirlier''. The female characters were of lesser significance in the play but were rendered convincingly by Bonner, Eugenie Blair, and Annie Boudinot.<ref>''Amusements'', ''[[Washington Post]]'', December 18, 1883, p. 2.</ref>
In May 1885 Bonner acted the part of ''Cicely Blaine'', the heroine in ''Galley Slave'', adapted from the writing of [[Bartley Campbell]]. The plot of the play dealt with impediments in the path of love. The characters were Americans traveling in [[Europe]]. The settings included [[Venice, Italy]], [[Rome, Italy]], and different parts of [[France]].<ref>''The Opening of the Amusement Hall'', Waukesha Freeman, May 28, 1885, pg. 4.</ref> Bonner often played second to actress [[Margaret Mather]].<ref name="death"/>
Her appearance was compared to [[Lily Langtry]] and she was called "The ''[[New Jersey|New]]'' Jersey Lily".<ref name=nickname>''Those Who Amuse Us'', Fort Wayne Gazette, Sunday, February 25, 1883, p. 2.</ref>
==Death== Bonner was found dead in her New York City apartment on November 15, 1895, the apparent victim of an overdose of morphine. She had a sister, Myra Goodwin, who was also an actress, and predeceased her.<ref name="death">[http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn84024441/1895-11-16/ed-1/seq-6/ Catherine Goodwin Dead], ''Evening Times'' (Washington, DC), November 16, 1895.</ref>
